Basic Questions
Q1. What is Spring Framework?

Answer: Spring is an open-source Java framework that simplifies the development of Java applications by providing ready-made features and managing common infrastructure tasks.

Q2. Is Spring a programming language?

Answer: No. Spring is a framework built on top of Java.

Q3. Why is Spring popular?

Answer: Because it reduces boilerplate code, improves maintainability, supports testing, and provides many modules for enterprise development.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What problems does Spring solve?

Answer:

Reduces repetitive code
Improves maintainability
Encourages loosely coupled design
Simplifies testing
Provides modular architecture
Q5. Name some important Spring modules.

Answer:

Core
AOP
Data Access
ORM
MVC
Boot
Scenario-Based Question
Q6. Your company is building a large banking application. Why would you recommend Spring instead of writing everything using plain Java?

Answer:
Because Spring provides a structured framework, reduces repetitive code, supports modular design, simplifies testing, and includes features commonly required in enterprise applications.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is Maven?

Answer: Maven is an open-source build automation and dependency management tool used for Java projects.

Q2. What is a Build Tool?

Answer: A build tool automates tasks such as compiling code, running tests, managing dependencies, and packaging applications.

Q3. Why do we use Maven?

Answer: Maven automates the build process, manages dependencies, provides a standard project structure, and saves development time.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What is the difference between Java and Maven?

Answer: Java is a programming language used to write applications, while Maven is a build tool used to manage and build Java projects.

Q5. What is a dependency?

Answer: A dependency is an external library that a project requires to function.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. Your teammate manually downloads all JAR files for a Spring project. What would you suggest?

Answer: I would recommend using Maven. By declaring dependencies in pom.xml, Maven automatically downloads the required libraries and manages their versions, reducing manual work and errors.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is a Maven Project?

Answer: A Maven Project is a Java project that uses Maven to manage dependencies, automate builds, and follow a standard project structure.

Q2. Why do we create a Maven Project?

Answer: To automate project building, manage dependencies, and maintain a standard directory structure.

Q3. What is the purpose of the src/main/java folder?

Answer: It stores the application's Java source code.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What is the purpose of the target folder?

Answer: It stores the compiled classes and packaged output (such as JAR files) after the project is built.

Q5. What is the difference between a Java Project and a Maven Project?

Answer: A Java Project requires manual dependency management and may not follow a standard structure, while a Maven Project automates dependency management and uses a standard directory layout.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. Your teammate manually creates folders and copies JAR files into every project. What would you suggest?

Answer: I would recommend creating a Maven Project. Maven automatically provides a standard structure and manages dependencies through pom.xml, making the project easier to maintain.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is a dependency?

Answer: A dependency is an external library or framework required by a project to provide additional functionality.

Q2. What is the purpose of pom.xml?

Answer: pom.xml stores the project's configuration, dependencies, plugins, and build information.

Q3. Why do we add Spring dependencies?

Answer: To use Spring classes and features in our Java project.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What are the three important tags inside a dependency?

Answer:

groupId
artifactId
version
Q5. Where does Maven download dependencies from?

Answer: By default, Maven downloads dependencies from the Maven Central Repository.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. You added a Spring dependency to pom.xml, but the library did not appear in your project. What would you check first?

Answer: I would check:

Whether the internet connection is available.
Whether the dependency coordinates (groupId, artifactId, version) are correct.
Whether Maven has refreshed/reloaded the project successfully.

Q1. What is Maven configuration?

Answer: Maven configuration is the process of defining project settings in pom.xml, including dependencies, Java version, plugins, and build information.

Q2. Which file is used to configure Maven?

Answer: pom.xml.

Q3. Why do we configure the Java version in Maven?

Answer: To ensure Maven compiles the project using the correct Java version.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What is the purpose of the <properties> section?

Answer: It stores project properties, such as the Java compiler source and target versions.

Q5. What is the purpose of plugins in Maven?

Answer: Plugins extend Maven's functionality, enabling tasks like compiling code, packaging applications, generating reports, and more.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. Your project compiles with Java 17, but another developer is using Java 21. How can Maven help?

Answer: Configure the Java source and target versions in pom.xml. Maven will then compile the project using the specified version, helping maintain consistency across different development environments.

Q1. What is IoC?

Answer:
IoC (Inversion of Control) is the principle where the responsibility of creating and managing objects is transferred from the programmer to the Spring Framework.

Q2. What is the IoC Container?

Answer:
The IoC Container is a part of the Spring Framework that creates, manages, stores, and provides objects (beans) throughout the application.

Q3. Why do we need the IoC Container?

Answer:
It automates object creation and management, reduces manual coding, promotes loose coupling, and makes applications easier to maintain and test.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What does "Control" mean in IoC?

Answer:
Control refers to the responsibility of creating and managing objects.

Q5. Why is it called "Inversion" of Control?

Answer:
Because the responsibility of object creation is reversed—instead of the developer creating objects, the Spring Framework creates and manages them.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. You notice many new statements scattered across a large Java project. What issue could this indicate?

Answer:
It may indicate excessive manual object creation, leading to tight coupling and maintenance challenges. Using the Spring IoC Container can centralize object creation and improve flexibility.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is XML Configuration in Spring?

Answer: XML Configuration is the process of configuring the Spring IoC Container using an XML file (typically beans.xml) to define Beans and their relationships.

Q2. What is the purpose of beans.xml?

Answer: It stores Bean definitions and configuration information for the Spring IoC Container.

Q3. What does the <bean> tag do?

Answer: It tells Spring to create and manage an object of the specified class.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What is the purpose of the id attribute?

Answer: It uniquely identifies a Bean inside the Spring IoC Container.

Q5. What is the purpose of the class attribute?

Answer: It specifies the fully qualified Java class whose object Spring should create.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. You remove a <bean> definition from beans.xml, but your application still requests that Bean. What will happen?

Answer: Spring will not find the Bean in the IoC Container, and an exception will be thrown when the application tries to retrieve it.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is a Spring Bean?

Answer: A Spring Bean is an object that is created, managed, and maintained by the Spring IoC Container.

Q2. What is a dependency?

Answer: A dependency is an object that another object requires to perform its work.

Q3. Is every Java object a Spring Bean?

Answer: No. Only objects created and managed by the Spring IoC Container are Spring Beans.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Why do we define Beans in Spring?

Answer: To allow the IoC Container to create, manage, and provide objects automatically.

Q5. Why are dependencies important?

Answer: Most real-world classes require other classes to perform their tasks. Spring manages these relationships automatically, reducing manual work and promoting loose coupling.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6. A Car class requires an Engine object. In a Spring application, who should create these objects?

Answer: The Spring IoC Container should create both the Car Bean and the Engine Bean and manage their relationship.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is ApplicationContext?

Answer:

ApplicationContext is the most commonly used implementation of the Spring IoC Container. It creates, manages, and provides Spring Beans.

Q2. Why do we use ApplicationContext?

Answer:

To create, manage, and retrieve Beans automatically instead of creating objects manually.

Q3. What does getBean() do?

Answer:

It retrieves a Bean from the Spring IoC Container.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Does ApplicationContext create Beans automatically?

Answer:

Yes. By default, it creates singleton Beans when the container starts (eager initialization).

Q5. Which configuration file does ClassPathXmlApplicationContext read?

Answer:

beans.xml (or any XML configuration file specified by the developer).

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

You wrote:

ApplicationContext context =
        new ClassPathXmlApplicationContext("beans.xml");

But beans.xml contains no Bean with ID "student".

What happens?

Answer:

When context.getBean("student") is called, Spring throws a NoSuchBeanDefinitionException because no Bean with that ID exists.

Q1. What is BeanFactory?

Answer:

BeanFactory is the basic implementation of the Spring IoC Container. It creates, manages, and provides Beans.

Q2. What is the main feature of BeanFactory?

Answer:

Lazy Loading—Beans are created only when they are requested.

Q3. What is Lazy Loading?

Answer:

Lazy Loading means creating an object only when it is needed, rather than creating it at application startup.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Does BeanFactory create all Beans when the application starts?

Answer:

No. It creates Beans only when getBean() is called.

Q5. Is BeanFactory commonly used in modern Spring applications?

Answer:

No. Modern applications usually use ApplicationContext because it provides additional enterprise features.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

Your application contains 1,000 Beans, but only 50 are used during execution.

Which container would consume less memory initially?

Answer:

BeanFactory, because it uses Lazy Loading and creates only the Beans that are actually requested.

Q1. What is an annotation?

Answer:

An annotation is a special marker in Java that provides metadata about the code. In Spring, annotations are used to configure and manage Beans.

Q2. Why did Spring introduce annotations?

Answer:

To reduce XML configuration, improve readability, and simplify Bean configuration.

Q3. Which symbol is used for annotations?

Answer:

The @ symbol.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Which approach is preferred in modern Spring projects?

Answer:

Annotation-based configuration.

Q5. Does an annotation itself create the Bean?

Answer:

No.

The annotation marks the class.

The Spring IoC Container, together with component scanning, detects the annotation and creates the Bean.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

You add @Component to a class, but Spring doesn't create a Bean.

What could be the reason?

Answer:

One common reason is that component scanning is not enabled or the package containing the class is not being scanned.

We'll learn this in the next sub-topic.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is Component Scanning?

Answer:

Component Scanning is the process by which Spring automatically searches packages for annotated classes and creates Beans.

Q2. Why do we need Component Scanning?

Answer:

Without Component Scanning, Spring cannot discover classes annotated with @Component, @Service, @Repository, or @Controller.

Q3. Which annotation is used for Component Scanning?

Answer:

@ComponentScan

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What does @ComponentScan("com.demo") mean?

Answer:

It tells Spring to scan the com.demo package for Spring-managed components.

Q5. What happens if you forget @ComponentScan?

Answer:

Spring won't detect annotated classes, so the corresponding Beans won't be created.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

Your Student class has @Component, but context.getBean(Student.class) throws an exception.

What could be the reason?

Answer:

One possible reason is that the package containing Student is not included in Component Scanning.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is @Component?

Answer:

@Component is a Spring stereotype annotation used to mark a class as a Spring-managed Bean.

Q2. What happens after adding @Component?

Answer:

If Component Scanning is enabled, Spring detects the class and registers it as a Bean in the IoC Container.

Q3. Does @Component create the Bean?

Answer:

No.

@Component only marks the class.

The Spring IoC Container creates the Bean after Component Scanning.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Can @Component work without @ComponentScan?

Answer:

No. Spring must scan the package to discover classes annotated with @Component.

Q5. When should you use @Component?

Answer:

Use @Component for general-purpose classes that don't belong specifically to the service, repository, or controller layers.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

You annotated a class with @Component, but Spring throws NoSuchBeanDefinitionException.

What could be the reason?

Answer:

The class's package may not be included in @ComponentScan, so Spring never discovered and registered the Bean.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is @Service?

Answer:

@Service is a Spring stereotype annotation used to mark a class as part of the business logic layer. Spring detects it during component scanning and registers it as a Bean.

Q2. Why do we use @Service?

Answer:

To clearly indicate that a class contains business logic and should be managed by the Spring IoC Container.

Q3. Does @Service create a Bean?

Answer:

Not by itself.

@Service marks the class, Component Scanning finds it, and the Spring IoC Container creates and manages the Bean.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What kind of methods belong in a Service class?

Answer:

Methods that implement business rules, such as calculations, validations, payment processing, order management, or interest calculation.

Q5. Can @Component replace @Service?

Answer:

Yes, technically it can because @Service is a specialized form of @Component. However, using @Service is recommended because it clearly communicates that the class belongs to the business logic layer.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

You're developing an online shopping application. Where should the method calculateDiscount() be placed?

Answer:

Inside a class annotated with @Service, because discount calculation is business logic.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is @Repository?

Answer:

@Repository is a Spring stereotype annotation used to mark a class responsible for database operations. Spring detects it during component scanning and manages it as a Bean.

Q2. What is the purpose of @Repository?

Answer:

To perform database operations such as inserting, updating, deleting, and retrieving data.

Q3. Which layer uses @Repository?

Answer:

The Data Access Layer (Repository/DAO Layer).

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Can business logic be written inside a Repository?

Answer:

No. Business logic belongs in the Service Layer. A Repository should only contain database-related operations.

Q5. What is CRUD?

Answer:

CRUD stands for:

C → Create
R → Read
U → Update
D → Delete

These are the basic database operations performed by a Repository.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

You're developing a Student Management System. Where should the method saveStudent() be placed?

Answer:

Inside a class annotated with @Repository, because saving data is a database operation.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is @Controller?

Answer:

@Controller is a Spring stereotype annotation used to mark a class that handles user requests and returns responses.

Q2. What is the role of a Controller?

Answer:

The Controller receives requests from the client, calls the Service layer to process them, and returns the appropriate response.

Q3. Which layer does @Controller belong to?

Answer:

The Presentation Layer (Web Layer).

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Should business logic be written inside a Controller?

Answer:

No. Business logic belongs in the Service Layer. The Controller should focus on request handling.

Q5. Can a Controller directly access the database?

Answer:

Ideally, no. The Controller should call the Service layer, which in turn calls the Repository layer.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

A user clicks the "Check Balance" button in a banking application. Which layer receives the request first?

Answer:

The Controller Layer receives the request first and then forwards it to the Service layer.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is Java-based Configuration?

Answer:

Java-based Configuration is the process of configuring Spring using Java classes instead of XML.

Q2. What is @Configuration?

Answer:

@Configuration marks a class as a Spring configuration class that contains Bean definitions.

Q3. What is @Bean?

Answer:

@Bean marks a method whose return value should be registered as a Spring Bean.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What is the difference between @Component and @Bean?

Answer:

@Component is placed on a class and relies on component scanning. @Bean is placed on a method inside a @Configuration class and explicitly defines how a Bean should be created.

Q5. Why is Java-based Configuration preferred over XML?

Answer:

Because it provides better readability, compile-time checking, IDE support, and easier maintenance.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

You are using a third-party library, and you cannot modify its classes to add @Component. How can you register one of its objects as a Spring Bean?

Answer:

Create a @Configuration class and define a @Bean method that returns an instance of the third-party class.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is Hybrid Configuration?

Answer:

Hybrid Configuration means using both XML configuration and Java-based configuration together in the same Spring application.

Q2. Why do companies use Hybrid Configuration?

Answer:

To gradually migrate legacy XML-based applications to modern Java-based configuration without rewriting the entire project.

Q3. Can XML and Java Configuration work together?

Answer:

Yes. Spring supports using both XML and Java configuration in the same application.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Is Hybrid Configuration recommended for new Spring Boot projects?

Answer:

No. New Spring Boot projects usually use Java-based configuration and annotations. Hybrid configuration is mainly used during migration or when maintaining legacy systems.

Q5. Which configuration style is preferred today?

Answer:

Java-based configuration with annotations (@Configuration, @Bean, @Component, etc.) is preferred in modern Spring applications.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

Your company has a Spring application with 800 Bean definitions in beans.xml. Management wants to adopt Spring Boot without disrupting the existing system. What approach would you recommend?

Answer:

Use Hybrid Configuration. Keep the existing XML configuration working while gradually introducing Java-based configuration for new or refactored components.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is Dependency Injection?

Answer:

Dependency Injection is a design pattern where Spring provides required dependencies (objects) to a class instead of the class creating them manually.

Q2. What is a dependency?

Answer:

A dependency is an object that another object needs to perform its work.

Q3. What is injection?

Answer:

Injection means providing a dependency from outside rather than creating it inside the class.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Why do we use Dependency Injection?

Answer:

To reduce tight coupling, improve maintainability, simplify testing, and let Spring manage object creation.

Q5. What is the relationship between IoC and DI?

Answer:

IoC is the overall design principle, and Dependency Injection is one technique used by Spring to implement IoC.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

A StudentService class creates its own StudentRepository object using new StudentRepository(). What design issue does this cause, and how can Spring solve it?

Answer:

It creates tight coupling because StudentService is directly responsible for creating its dependency. Spring solves this by creating the StudentRepository Bean and injecting it into StudentService using Dependency Injection.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is Constructor Injection?

Answer:

Constructor Injection is a type of Dependency Injection where Spring provides required dependencies through the constructor of a class.

Q2. Why is Constructor Injection preferred?

Answer:

Because it ensures mandatory dependencies are available when the object is created, promotes loose coupling, and improves testability.

Q3. Who injects the dependency in Spring?

Answer:

The Spring IoC Container injects the dependency.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Can Constructor Injection work without Spring?

Answer:

Yes. Constructor Injection is a general object-oriented design pattern. Spring automates the process of providing constructor arguments.

Q5. When should you choose Constructor Injection?

Answer:

When a dependency is required for the object to function correctly.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

A Car cannot function without an Engine. Which type of Dependency Injection is more appropriate?

Answer:

Constructor Injection, because the Engine is a mandatory dependency.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is Setter Injection?

Answer:

Setter Injection is a type of Dependency Injection where Spring injects dependencies through setter methods.

Q2. Which method is used in Setter Injection?

Answer:

A setter method, such as setEngine(Engine engine).

Q3. When should Setter Injection be used?

Answer:

When a dependency is optional or may need to be modified after object creation.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What XML tag is used for Setter Injection?

Answer:

The <property> tag.

Q5. Can Setter Injection work without Spring?

Answer:

Yes. It is a general object-oriented design pattern. Spring automates the process.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

An application has an optional NotificationService. Sometimes it sends emails, and sometimes notifications are disabled.

Which injection type is more suitable?

Answer:

Setter Injection, because the dependency is optional and can be configured later.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is @Autowired?

Answer:

@Autowired is a Spring annotation that automatically injects a required Bean into another Bean.

Q2. What is Autowiring?

Answer:

Autowiring is the process by which Spring automatically finds and injects required dependencies.

Q3. Who performs Autowiring?

Answer:

The Spring IoC Container.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Where can @Autowired be used?

Answer:

It can be used on:

Fields
Setter methods
Constructors
Q5. Which form of @Autowired is recommended?

Answer:

Constructor Injection, because it supports immutable dependencies, improves testability, and ensures required dependencies are available.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

Your application has two Beans of type Engine: PetrolEngine and DieselEngine. You write:

@Autowired
private Engine engine;

What happens?

Answer:

Spring cannot determine which Bean to inject and throws a NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException. This can be resolved using @Qualifier, which you'll learn next.

Basic Questions
Q1. What is @Qualifier?

Answer:

@Qualifier is a Spring annotation used with @Autowired to specify which Bean should be injected when multiple Beans of the same type are available.

Q2. Why do we use @Qualifier?

Answer:

To resolve ambiguity when Spring finds more than one matching Bean during Autowiring.

Q3. Can @Qualifier be used without @Autowired?

Answer:

In typical dependency injection scenarios, @Qualifier is used together with @Autowired (or another injection annotation) because its purpose is to narrow the Bean selection.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. What happens if @Qualifier is not used and two Beans of the same type exist?

Answer:

Spring throws a NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException because it cannot determine which Bean to inject.

Q5. Can @Qualifier be used with Constructor Injection?

Answer:

Yes. It can be used with constructor parameters, setter methods, and field injection.

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

Your application contains:

EmailService

SMSService

Both implement:

NotificationService

How do you inject only EmailService?

Answer:

@Autowired
@Qualifier("emailService")
private NotificationService notificationService;

14. Interview Questions
Basic Questions
Q1. What is @Inject?

Answer:

@Inject is a standard Java (JSR-330) annotation used for dependency injection. Spring supports it as an alternative to @Autowired.

Q2. What is @Resource?

Answer:

@Resource is a Jakarta annotation used for dependency injection. It primarily injects Beans by their name.

Q3. What is the main difference between @Autowired and @Resource?

Answer:

@Autowired injects by type, whereas @Resource primarily injects by name.

Intermediate Questions
Q4. Is @Inject a Spring annotation?

Answer:

No. It is defined by the Java standard (JSR-330), but Spring supports it.

Q5. Which annotation is most commonly used in Spring Boot?

Answer:

@Autowired (or constructor injection without explicitly writing @Autowired on a single constructor).

Scenario-Based Question
Q6.

Two Beans implement the PaymentService interface:

upiPayment
cardPayment

You want to inject upiPayment by its Bean name. Which annotation can you use?

Answer:

@Resource(name = "upiPayment")
private PaymentService paymentService;